MPS Forensic package

Introduction

The following is meant to get you started with this software for processing data from Massively Parallel Sequencing (MPS) for forensics applications.

This MPS Forensics software provides a simple point-and-click interface to run several bioinformatics software pipelines for forensic analysis of DNA data on a Ubuntu Linux computer system. Your system must be running Ubuntu Linux 14.04 LTS or later for the MPS Forensics package to work.

Once the MPS Forensics package is fully installed (find installation instructions below) there are icons on the user's Desktop for:

  • starting the MPS Forensics application; and

  • opening the directory (you might call it a folder) where MPS Forensics results are stored.

Once the program is started, it's use may be relatively intuitive.

There is a Help button on the home page of MPS Forensics. It opens a browser with help information for the application.

You can choose a pipeline (use the TABs near the top of the window). You will usually need to choose the data file you intend to process. Set all your options and press the Run button near the bottom. Some pipelines take quite a while to run.

You need system administrator privileges (rights) to do an initial install on your computer. After that, any user on the system can install the MPS Forensics package to run in their own user space.

A short introduction to Ubuntu Linux

Ubuntu Linux has a similar (but not identical) interface to other modern operating systems. On a newly installed Ubuntu Linux system, the top left of the screen looks something like the image on the left.

From top to bottom, the icons are:

  1. the Ubuntu Application finder (Ubuntu logo)

  2. the File finder/navigator (file drawer)

  3. Firefox a web browser (foxy thingy on a globe)

  4. the Terminal icon (black rectangle with grey border)

  5. the Application installer (bag with 'A' on it)

Generally, these icons and their associated applications work the same or similarly to comparable applications on MS Windows or on an Apple Mac. Basically, you can click on the icon in the task bar to start the application.

Possibly, the Terminal icon isn't present. That issue is addressed below.

Initial installation

The MPS Forensics package is designed to install on a Ubuntu Linux system 14.04 LTS or 16.04 LTS. You need at least 20GB of disk free though you may need more to store your data and the results. Warning: installation can be slow on a Virtual Machine since the network seems relatively slow.

After you have started your Ubuntu Linux computer and logged in, there are two installation methods for the MPS Forensics software.

  • a command line install from the terminal application

  • a point-and-click installation.

Both installation methods are described below. If you do not succeed with one of them, you can try the other. There are always lots of different ways to achieve a result on a Unix/Linux system.

Command line install

This is easiest way to install the software but some people might regard command line methods as a bit old fashioned.

First, start a terminal. Either:

  • click on the Terminal icon in the task bar; or

  • click on the application icon (usually) at the top left of the Ubuntu screen.

When you click on Ubuntu's application finder/starter icon, the finder pops up a window that lets you type the name of an application. We want the terminal application. If you type terminal (without the quotes), the top left of the screen will look like this:



Double-click the Terminal application and a box like the following will appear (the markings and letter won't be exactly the same, but you'll get the idea).



This is a Linux terminal or command-line interface.

About the Linux Terminal

Normally, the Terminal icon will disappear from the task bar when the Terminal is finished. To keep the Terminal icon in the task bar (so you can click on it to start a new Terminal), right click on the icon and choose Lock to Launcher.

You can have several Terminals running at the same time, if you want.

The line that ends in '$' is called the 'dollar-prompt and the white rectangle following it is the 'text cursor'. You can type commands on the keyboard, and they will appear at the cursor. Type the following command (the bit after the $; note that the space after 'cd' is important), then press the Enter (or Return) key.

$ cd ~/Desktop

The terminal application will be like this:



All the stuff about bobb is about Bob Buckley's account. Bob used his computer to get these screen images. The machine he did it on is called bobb-VirtualBox expect that these names will be different on your computer.

Installing MPS Forensics software starts with getting the file called install_mpsforensics.sh onto your computer. The following commands are the easiest way to do this:

$ wget http://tinyurl.com/zvks3zd
$ mv zvks3zd install_mpsforensics.sh
$ ls -l

Make sure that you:

  • do not type the $ signs (the computer types then to indicate that it's ready for you to type your commands)

  • type the spaces that are in these commands

  • press the Enter or Return key (depending on your keyboard) at the end of each command (line). If you get a command wrong, you can edit it (using the arrow keys and the Backspace key to delete characters) up until you press the Enter/Return key.

When you have done the 3 commands above, your terminal screen should look something like this:



Now type the command:

$ source install_mpsforensics.sh

The computer will ask for your password. The screen will (should) look like this:



Type in your password and press Enter/Return you won't be able to see your password. If you get it wrong, it will ask again.

The install process takes quite a while. Lots of stuff will flash by on the screen and there may be some periods where little appears to be happening.

When it finishes, the terminal screen will look something like this:



If so, press Enter/Return (as instructed) and the MPS Forensics software is ready to run.

If not, something didn't work. You need to contact the software developers for help.

Point-and-click install of MPS Forensics

If you are unable to follow the instructions above for the command line install, you can try this method.

  1. Start a browser. A version of Firefox is usually installed as part of the Ubuntu Desktop system. Click on the Firefox icon in the task bar. The Firefox icon is shown above (near the start of this document).

Other browsers like Chrome or Chromium would also work. You may need to install these yourself (Ubuntu has a point-and-click application installer that can help though installing Chrome may be a bit tricky).

  1. Open the URL http://bobbuckley.net.au/work/ with your browser.

    If you can't get your browser to open the URL above, the following might work

    Use your browser to open the README file: the README file for MPS Forensics is available through the URL: http://tinyurl.com/hgooe9r (which really points to https://bitbucket.org/gdu_jcsmr/mpsforensics/raw/master/mpsfor-dist/README.html). If the file doesn't open as HTML (if it looks like a complicated text file), save the file first (using the File Save Page as option on the browser's menu) then open the saved file it should be named README.html with your browser (using the File Open File option on the browser's menu). You may need to find it in your directories look in your Home, Download and Desktop directories.

    If that still doesn't work, you may be able to use another computer to save README.html on a memory stick, then take the memory stick to your Linux computer; on the Linux computer, open the README.html file from the memory stick (using the browser's File Open File option). When you put a memory stick in a Ubuntu Linux system, it will usually appear in the /media directory. The Ubuntu Linux file browser has an icon on the task bar that looks like a filing cabinet drawer.

  2. Find (scroll down to) the point-and-click install instructions in the README file so you can click on this link: https://bitbucket.org/gdu_jcsmr/mpsforensics/src/master/mpsfor-dist/install_mpsforensics.sh. Save the file (page?) on your Desktop.

  3. Make the install_mpsforensics.sh file executable. It should be visible on your Desktop or maybe find it in your file browser. Right click on the file and and choose Properties from the menu (usually the last/bottom menu item). When the Properties window opens, click the Permissions tab and click/enable the Execute: Allow executing file as program option.

You also need to make the system actually run executable files. Start the file browser (filing cabinet icon), then choose Edit Preferences to open the Files Preferences window. Choose the Behaviour tab. Choose the Ask each time (or Run executable text files when they are opened) option.



You can close the window when done.

  1. Now run the installation script: double click on install_mpsforensics.sh. It will open a window asking:


Click the Run in Terminal button.

A screen will appear that looks a bit like this:


The progress of the installation tasks should be displayed.

If the install process is successful, it will eventually instruct you to press the Enter (or Return) key on your keyboard.


When the installation process is finished there should be two icons on the Desktop: one for starting the application and one to take you to the Results directory.

Notes

During the initial admin. installation, a log file is created in the system's /etc directory. Initially, the log file is called mpsforensics.log but once all the commands are run, it is moved to mpsforensics-done.log. This is the first place to look if anything goes wrong.

If the mpsforensics-done.log is present, the install script skips over the admin. install process. You can rename it (or maybe delete it) and rerun the install. The apt-get commands in the script will just report software that is already present so a re-run should be OK, nothing should break.

The second part of the installation process is performed by the MPSforensicsSetup.sh script or by running the install_mpsforensics.sh script. These scripts can be re-run. And you can also restart the user install process with these commands:

$ rm -rf ~/mpsforensics
$ . MPSforensicsSetup.sh
